00:44:27.970 --> 00:44:30.250
Often in the US and
in Europe, we think,

00:44:30.250 --> 00:44:33.880
all right, I pay
$100 for something.

00:44:33.880 --> 00:44:35.710
You think you paid $100 for it.

00:44:35.710 --> 00:44:39.850
Well, actually you paid
$97 roughly for it,

00:44:39.850 --> 00:44:43.660
and $2.75 went to
the payment system.

00:44:43.660 --> 00:44:47.350
And that $2.75 that went to
the payment system, most of it

00:44:47.350 --> 00:44:49.670
goes to what's called
the issuing bank.

00:44:49.670 --> 00:44:54.100
And again, the issuing
bank is the purchaser.

00:44:54.100 --> 00:44:57.390
The acquiring bank
is the merchant.

00:44:57.390 --> 00:45:01.970
So that merchant bank is
only getting $0.19 on average

00:45:01.970 --> 00:45:06.880
two years ago, the acquiring
bank, Bank of America,

00:45:06.880 --> 00:45:09.550
or whomever issued
the credit card.

00:45:09.550 --> 00:45:12.100
So the dominant part
of the economics

00:45:12.100 --> 00:45:14.660
here is on the credit card side.

00:45:14.660 --> 00:45:19.090
There's seven big companies
in America being the big four

00:45:19.090 --> 00:45:23.140
banks of Bank of America,
and Wells Fargo, and Citi,

00:45:23.140 --> 00:45:25.180
and Chase.

00:45:25.180 --> 00:45:29.140
But then Cap One is a
very big credit card bank.

00:45:29.140 --> 00:45:32.140
And then, of course,
American Express and Discover

00:45:32.140 --> 00:45:33.670
and the like.

00:45:33.670 --> 00:45:37.210
Those seven big banks are
the big issuing banks.

00:45:37.210 --> 00:45:42.670
But community banks, even
smaller banks across the land,

00:45:42.670 --> 00:45:47.440
will issue credit cards,
and they get that roughly $2

00:45:47.440 --> 00:45:50.542
out of $100 purchase.

00:45:50.542 --> 00:45:51.750
Now, what do they do with it?

00:45:51.750 --> 00:45:54.680
Part of it is the
rewards program.

00:45:54.680 --> 00:45:58.670
And wrapped up inside of all
this is an incentive system

00:45:58.670 --> 00:46:04.430
that issuing banks are using
part of that $2.20 on average,

00:46:04.430 --> 00:46:07.160
on average about $1--

00:46:07.160 --> 00:46:10.490
I think the national
average recently was $1.06.

00:46:10.490 --> 00:46:13.550
If you take all the
different rewards programs,

00:46:13.550 --> 00:46:15.430
they come back.

00:46:15.430 --> 00:46:17.510
So you buy something for $100.

00:46:17.510 --> 00:46:21.120
$2.20 goes to your issuing bank.

00:46:21.120 --> 00:46:25.370
$1 might come back
to you as a reward.

00:46:25.370 --> 00:46:27.940
And it makes behavioral
sciences important

00:46:27.940 --> 00:46:30.010
and makes this stuff sticky.

00:46:30.010 --> 00:46:35.540
It makes us loyal to our cards
in a way that pure economics,

00:46:35.540 --> 00:46:37.510
you would think, that
it would be easier

00:46:37.510 --> 00:46:39.460
to disrupt this space.

00:46:39.460 --> 00:46:42.120
So I wouldn't put aside some
of these reward programs

00:46:42.120 --> 00:46:43.870
when you're thinking
about, all right, I'm

00:46:43.870 --> 00:46:44.920
going to be a disrupter.

00:46:44.920 --> 00:46:47.860
I'm going to break
into the payment space.

00:46:47.860 --> 00:46:52.640
The credit card companies, they
have a point of view on this,

00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:53.140
too.

00:46:53.140 --> 00:46:56.770
And they're going to want to
protect their market share.

