00:51:37.690 --> 00:51:41.890
Real-time gross settlements
is this conceptual framework

00:51:41.890 --> 00:51:44.400
that we are all familiar
with in one way or the other.

00:51:44.400 --> 00:51:53.180
Can I move a digital
instruction to move money

00:51:53.180 --> 00:51:58.400
and to have the settlement
be relatively fast,

00:51:58.400 --> 00:52:01.730
real-time gross settlement?

00:52:01.730 --> 00:52:03.090
What's the word "gross" mean?

00:52:03.090 --> 00:52:05.750
It means that we're
not net settling.

00:52:05.750 --> 00:52:09.290
If you run a settlement system
with millions of checks coming

00:52:09.290 --> 00:52:13.670
into a warehouse-- and that's
literally how the system

00:52:13.670 --> 00:52:18.080
of check clearing used to
work in New York and elsewhere

00:52:18.080 --> 00:52:20.840
in this country--

00:52:20.840 --> 00:52:22.650
you can actually net settle.

00:52:22.650 --> 00:52:25.940
You can say, well, there's
these checks coming in

00:52:25.940 --> 00:52:29.540
from Bank of America to
Wells Fargo and these checks

00:52:29.540 --> 00:52:31.640
from Wells Fargo
to Bank of America.

00:52:31.640 --> 00:52:35.690
Let's net these settlements
off against each other.

00:52:35.690 --> 00:52:37.700
But if you do
something in real-time,

00:52:37.700 --> 00:52:39.680
if you do it almost
instantaneous,

00:52:39.680 --> 00:52:40.670
it has to be gross.

00:52:40.670 --> 00:52:43.310
You can't net the
payment instructions

00:52:43.310 --> 00:52:45.470
between the various banks.

00:52:45.470 --> 00:52:49.430
Real-time gross settlement is
used for large value payments

00:52:49.430 --> 00:52:51.080
and has been used
for large value

00:52:51.080 --> 00:52:52.780
payments for quite some time.

00:52:52.780 --> 00:52:58.700
In fact, the early large value
model is the Fedwire, 1970.

00:52:58.700 --> 00:53:01.820
That's 50 years of
technology that we've

00:53:01.820 --> 00:53:04.580
had the Fedwire,
meaning I can do

00:53:04.580 --> 00:53:06.760
what's called a
wire instruction.

00:53:06.760 --> 00:53:09.950
But in the United
Kingdom, we had CHAPS.

00:53:09.950 --> 00:53:13.700
And in China--

00:53:13.700 --> 00:53:19.700
I'm going to mispronounce
it, but C-N-A-P-S high-value

00:53:19.700 --> 00:53:22.250
payment system, the
Eurozone TARGET.

00:53:22.250 --> 00:53:26.300
2002 is actually when
the Eurozone was created.

00:53:26.300 --> 00:53:29.120
So we've had large value models.

00:53:29.120 --> 00:53:31.730
Coupled with that is
something called SWIFT.

00:53:31.730 --> 00:53:34.400
SWIFT is just a
messaging company.

00:53:34.400 --> 00:53:38.210
SWIFT, the Society for
Worldwide Interbank Financial

00:53:38.210 --> 00:53:41.630
Telecommunications,
I think, it's

00:53:41.630 --> 00:53:46.730
basically to send messages to
facilitate these interbank.

00:53:46.730 --> 00:53:49.310
The question in the
last 10 to 15 years

00:53:49.310 --> 00:53:53.045
is, can we move from
large value to just

00:53:53.045 --> 00:53:58.640
you and me, in essence, what we
think we're doing with Venmo?

00:53:58.640 --> 00:54:03.320
Can I move you money
rapidly instantaneously?

00:54:03.320 --> 00:54:05.975
And some countries have
actually moved forward.

00:54:08.660 --> 00:54:11.010
It's called real-time retail.

00:54:11.010 --> 00:54:14.450
And the important thing is
it's retail instant payments.

00:54:14.450 --> 00:54:18.610
Now, a lot of people don't call
it real-time retail instant.

00:54:18.610 --> 00:54:21.150
A lot of people would just
call it 24 hours a day,

00:54:21.150 --> 00:54:25.430
7 days a week, or some
people might call it RTGS.

00:54:25.430 --> 00:54:27.740
But fundamentally, the
question is, can we

00:54:27.740 --> 00:54:34.660
do what the Fed the Reserve
of the US did 50 years ago

00:54:34.660 --> 00:54:39.040
and the United Kingdom
did nearly 40 years ago?

00:54:39.040 --> 00:54:41.900
Can we do that for
the retail public,

00:54:41.900 --> 00:54:44.530
and can we do it 24
hours a day, 7 days

00:54:44.530 --> 00:54:46.940
a week, every day of the year?

00:54:46.940 --> 00:54:49.720
And the answer is yes,
the technology exists.

00:54:49.720 --> 00:54:52.450
I'm listing here seven
or eight countries

00:54:52.450 --> 00:54:56.110
that either have
instantaneous payment

00:54:56.110 --> 00:54:59.000
systems or near instantaneous.

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:01.840
Some of these are not
literally instantaneous.

00:55:01.840 --> 00:55:05.960
A couple of them are
three cycles a day

00:55:05.960 --> 00:55:08.500
where they do this
three times a day.

00:55:08.500 --> 00:55:10.600
And I can't remember
each country,

00:55:10.600 --> 00:55:13.420
but you can see it's
relatively recent.

00:55:13.420 --> 00:55:15.290
And then the US.

00:55:15.290 --> 00:55:19.210
With the US projects, we
have this split system.

00:55:19.210 --> 00:55:24.340
The clearing house is owned
by 24 major banks in the US,

00:55:24.340 --> 00:55:28.380
and it's been around
since the 1850s.

00:55:28.380 --> 00:55:31.300
The clearing house
by 2017 said, we

00:55:31.300 --> 00:55:34.750
want to provide a
real-time payment network.

00:55:34.750 --> 00:55:38.560
But it's really buying
amongst these 24 major banks,

00:55:38.560 --> 00:55:41.560
all the big banks in the US.

00:55:41.560 --> 00:55:46.270
The Federal Reserve at first
seemed comfortable with that.

00:55:46.270 --> 00:55:49.690
And then frankly, the rest
of the banking community,

00:55:49.690 --> 00:55:54.740
the banks that weren't the
top 24 said, no, not really.

00:55:54.740 --> 00:55:56.170
And they went to Congress.

00:55:56.170 --> 00:56:00.190
They went to the US Congress,
and many members of Congress

00:56:00.190 --> 00:56:03.490
got involved on behalf
of community banks.

00:56:03.490 --> 00:56:05.440
There's 5,000 or
6,000 banks that

00:56:05.440 --> 00:56:08.800
are not direct members
of the clearinghouse.

00:56:08.800 --> 00:56:13.570
And so now the Federal Reserve
is standing up FedNow service.

00:56:13.570 --> 00:56:16.070
And you can see this in
Lael Brainard's speech.

00:56:16.070 --> 00:56:19.830
Now, FedNow service
is also meant

00:56:19.830 --> 00:56:22.560
to be like a public
utility rather than

00:56:22.560 --> 00:56:25.050
controlled by these 24 banks.

00:56:25.050 --> 00:56:27.810
And so there's some interesting
dynamics back and forth

00:56:27.810 --> 00:56:29.140
in the competition.

00:56:29.140 --> 00:56:31.860
The clearinghouse real-time
payment network probably

00:56:31.860 --> 00:56:36.420
will up its game, and FedNow
will come along as well.

00:56:36.420 --> 00:56:39.420
Some said that the announcement
last year by the Federal

00:56:39.420 --> 00:56:41.970
Reserve was in reaction
to Facebook Libra,

00:56:41.970 --> 00:56:45.120
and maybe that spurred
this a little bit,

00:56:45.120 --> 00:56:46.590
that the official
sector was then

00:56:46.590 --> 00:56:49.560
competing with Facebook
because the announcement came

00:56:49.560 --> 00:56:51.150
just weeks after.

00:56:51.150 --> 00:56:54.480
Now, I would imagine the Federal
Reserve was working on it

00:56:54.480 --> 00:56:56.310
a long time beforehand.

00:56:56.310 --> 00:56:58.270
And we'll close out
this lecture today

00:56:58.270 --> 00:57:03.780
on when China's digital currency
electronic payments program.

00:57:03.780 --> 00:57:06.120
China and the Federal
Reserve in the US

00:57:06.120 --> 00:57:10.350
both had major announcements
right after Facebook Libra.

00:57:10.350 --> 00:57:14.940
This project, FedNow, and
China's, both had been--

00:57:14.940 --> 00:57:18.330
work had been done, but it
feels like the announcements

00:57:18.330 --> 00:57:22.140
were accelerated and
in reaction a bit.

00:57:22.140 --> 00:57:25.290
We don't know for
sure, of course.

00:57:25.290 --> 00:57:27.486
Questions, Romain?

00:57:27.486 --> 00:57:28.885
ROMAIN: None so far, Gary.

