GARY GENSLER: All right.

00:57:30.040 --> 00:57:31.810
So what's the payment landscape?

00:57:31.810 --> 00:57:33.010
Who are the companies?

00:57:33.010 --> 00:57:34.690
Well, we've talked
about Big Tech.

00:57:34.690 --> 00:57:38.670
And I'm glad, Luke,
I think I have

00:57:38.670 --> 00:57:41.920
KakaoPay on there thankfully.

00:57:41.920 --> 00:57:44.320
I should have had
LINE Pay as well.

00:57:44.320 --> 00:57:48.490
But Big Tech, OK, we've chatted
a little bit about that.

00:57:48.490 --> 00:57:52.920
And then there's, of course,
a bunch of unicorn startups.

00:57:52.920 --> 00:57:55.560
I could have put another
half dozen to a dozen,

00:57:55.560 --> 00:58:00.250
unicorn being $1 billion
of value or more.

00:58:00.250 --> 00:58:03.490
But each of these startups
have a little bit different way

00:58:03.490 --> 00:58:06.220
that they've broken
into this space.

00:58:06.220 --> 00:58:10.280
Plaid, which we've chatted
a little bit about,

00:58:10.280 --> 00:58:14.860
Plaid is in this space because
they came in through open APIs

00:58:14.860 --> 00:58:18.670
and facilitating the
software in the system.

00:58:18.670 --> 00:58:23.360
Ripple is a cryptocurrency
type company.

00:58:23.360 --> 00:58:25.900
One97 is in India.

00:58:25.900 --> 00:58:28.540
It's really-- I could even
have put that in the Big Tech

00:58:28.540 --> 00:58:31.210
because they started,
I think, Paytm.

00:58:31.210 --> 00:58:35.850
NewBank addressed it a little
bit from being a challenger

00:58:35.850 --> 00:58:37.800
bank, and we're going
to be talking about that

00:58:37.800 --> 00:58:38.800
in a couple of lectures.

00:58:38.800 --> 00:58:42.370
Toast picks a sector,
and they really

00:58:42.370 --> 00:58:45.540
dominate the restaurant sector.

00:58:45.540 --> 00:58:48.280
But they initially were
getting into payments

00:58:48.280 --> 00:58:49.660
because they were into tablets.

00:58:49.660 --> 00:58:53.890
So each has a bit of
a different story.

00:58:53.890 --> 00:58:56.650
Brex was about startups
and facilitating

00:58:56.650 --> 00:58:57.820
credit for startups.

00:58:57.820 --> 00:59:02.300
TransferWise was cross-border,
as we talked about earlier.

00:59:02.300 --> 00:59:06.040
So they each found a
strategy to build themselves

00:59:06.040 --> 00:59:07.560
into this place.

00:59:07.560 --> 00:59:12.160
But let's just talk about Alipay
and WeChat Pay for a moment.

00:59:12.160 --> 00:59:15.070
This is even dated because
this is nearly a year old,

00:59:15.070 --> 00:59:19.060
but this is their user base
in the last seven years,

00:59:19.060 --> 00:59:23.200
this remarkable growth
of usage between Alipay

00:59:23.200 --> 00:59:27.400
and WeChat Pay in China,
both with approximately

00:59:27.400 --> 00:59:28.990
a billion users.

00:59:28.990 --> 00:59:31.180
It's thought that WeChat
Pay and Alipay now

00:59:31.180 --> 00:59:37.310
have 92% of the retail
payment space in China.

00:59:37.310 --> 00:59:41.390
And one of their
strategic approaches

00:59:41.390 --> 00:59:46.100
is that if you have a store
of value on an Alipay wallet

00:59:46.100 --> 00:59:50.870
and you move it to somebody
else within the Alipay system,

00:59:50.870 --> 00:59:53.240
as I understand it,
it's still 0 cost.

00:59:53.240 --> 00:59:57.980
If you jump out of service,
out of system, 10 basis points.

00:59:57.980 --> 01:00:01.580
But this conceptual framework--
and their pricing model

01:00:01.580 --> 01:00:04.700
could change at any time,
but their pricing model

01:00:04.700 --> 01:00:08.300
has been historically, if you
stay within the Alipay wallet

01:00:08.300 --> 01:00:12.690
system, heck of a
benefit in cost.

01:00:12.690 --> 01:00:16.570
So merchants then start to
want to pay their vendors.

01:00:16.570 --> 01:00:20.620
And merchants and customers
want to stay within those wallet

01:00:20.620 --> 01:00:23.920
systems to keep
those costs down,

01:00:23.920 --> 01:00:26.560
significant network effects.

01:00:26.560 --> 01:00:27.345
Romain?

01:00:27.345 --> 01:00:29.840
ROMAIN: Sijin has her hand up.

01:00:29.840 --> 01:00:30.855
GARY GENSLER: Please.

01:00:30.855 --> 01:00:31.770
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:00:31.770 --> 01:00:32.620
Hi.

01:00:32.620 --> 01:00:34.750
Just want to add one point.

01:00:34.750 --> 01:00:38.120
I think the social platform
base is really important,

01:00:38.120 --> 01:00:41.530
but another thing that
Alipay is so successful

01:00:41.530 --> 01:00:44.260
because it's working
closely with the government.

01:00:44.260 --> 01:00:50.170
For example, right now in China,
we can use a QR code in Alipay

01:00:50.170 --> 01:00:53.910
when we try to get
on the shuttle bus

01:00:53.910 --> 01:00:55.990
or we want to get a phone.

01:00:55.990 --> 01:00:58.690
We can use the Alipay
to pay that bill.

01:00:58.690 --> 01:01:02.470
So actually, the government is
encouraging all of the citizens

01:01:02.470 --> 01:01:05.758
to use this Alipay
and WeChat Pay.

01:01:05.758 --> 01:01:06.550
GARY GENSLER: Yeah.

01:01:06.550 --> 01:01:09.730
So there's incredible
collaboration,

01:01:09.730 --> 01:01:13.450
what you're talking
about, between government

01:01:13.450 --> 01:01:16.060
and these payments systems.

01:01:16.060 --> 01:01:18.140
And we've seen this
in India as well.

01:01:18.140 --> 01:01:21.040
India really
encouraged the uptake.

01:01:21.040 --> 01:01:24.700
And I could have put various
statistics in for India.

01:01:24.700 --> 01:01:26.590
They're a couple or
few years behind.

01:01:26.590 --> 01:01:31.450
They're not as robust
and developed in India.

01:01:31.450 --> 01:01:36.010
But this encouragement by the
official sector or the banking

01:01:36.010 --> 01:01:36.670
sector--

01:01:36.670 --> 01:01:39.880
sometimes in other countries,
it can be by the banking sector.

01:01:39.880 --> 01:01:43.330
But what's interesting in China,
and we'll close out on this,

01:01:43.330 --> 01:01:47.300
is now the Chinese
government is offering

01:01:47.300 --> 01:01:50.770
what one might say is a
complement or a competitor

01:01:50.770 --> 01:01:54.730
to WeChat and Alipay through
the Chinese digital currency

01:01:54.730 --> 01:01:57.700
electronic payment
project or DCEP.

01:01:57.700 --> 01:02:02.230
And so they've facilitated the
ramp up of Alipay and WeChat

01:02:02.230 --> 01:02:07.280
Pay, but now they're going to
have an alternative as well.

01:02:07.280 --> 01:02:08.500
So it's very interesting.

01:02:08.500 --> 01:02:11.230
And I think in part,
this is to facilitate

01:02:11.230 --> 01:02:14.560
the commercial banks were
losing a significant market

01:02:14.560 --> 01:02:18.070
share to Alipay and WeChat Pay,
that the Chinese government

01:02:18.070 --> 01:02:22.450
may well have been encouraged
to build their own--

01:02:22.450 --> 01:02:24.850
they call it the central
bank digital currency--

01:02:24.850 --> 01:02:29.110
but their own wallet
system, digital wallet,

01:02:29.110 --> 01:02:36.250
digital yuan that will look
a lot like Alipay and WeChat

01:02:36.250 --> 01:02:37.060
wallets.

01:02:37.060 --> 01:02:40.750
And in fact, this is all
being rolled out in 2020.

01:02:40.750 --> 01:02:44.560
But in fact, the
initial pronouncements

01:02:44.560 --> 01:02:48.370
say that it must be
accepted, so just

01:02:48.370 --> 01:02:51.970
as we have had multiple
centuries of laws that

01:02:51.970 --> 01:02:53.800
are called legal tender laws.

01:02:53.800 --> 01:02:56.590
And the legal tender
laws go all the way

01:02:56.590 --> 01:03:00.040
back to Genghis
Khan in China, where

01:03:00.040 --> 01:03:03.350
under the coercive
power of the state,

01:03:03.350 --> 01:03:07.060
you must accept in those
days the paper bark

01:03:07.060 --> 01:03:10.060
currency of Genghis
Khan, or in the US,

01:03:10.060 --> 01:03:13.070
you must accept the US
dollar for all debts

01:03:13.070 --> 01:03:14.440
public and private.

01:03:14.440 --> 01:03:16.360
Those are called
legal tender laws.

01:03:16.360 --> 01:03:18.970
Something similar is
happening right now in China

01:03:18.970 --> 01:03:22.480
that this DCEP will
have to be accepted,

01:03:22.480 --> 01:03:24.050
at first in certain cities.

01:03:24.050 --> 01:03:26.878
They're going to start,
I think, in two cities,

01:03:26.878 --> 01:03:28.420
and then they're
going to roll it out

01:03:28.420 --> 01:03:31.880
over time in other places.

01:03:31.880 --> 01:03:34.270
So now let's look
here in the US.

01:03:34.270 --> 01:03:36.670
And I picked
Facebook because they

01:03:36.670 --> 01:03:38.710
haven't been as successful.

01:03:38.710 --> 01:03:44.770
This remarkable platform,
Facebook is so ubiquitous,

01:03:44.770 --> 01:03:47.470
over 2 billion members
around the globe.

01:03:47.470 --> 01:03:50.130
They've tried multiple
times to get into payments

01:03:50.130 --> 01:03:52.630
starting 11 years ago.

01:03:52.630 --> 01:03:54.850
Virtual currency
in 15 currencies

01:03:54.850 --> 01:03:58.330
terminated in four
years, Facebook credit.

01:03:58.330 --> 01:04:02.290
They came about in 2015
Facebook Messenger.

01:04:02.290 --> 01:04:04.780
They started in the
US, UK, and France.

01:04:04.780 --> 01:04:09.230
By 2019, they rolled out
of France and the UK.

01:04:09.230 --> 01:04:13.400
They, in India, had a pilot
that for the longest time

01:04:13.400 --> 01:04:19.700
was in pilot
purgatory, in a sense.

01:04:19.700 --> 01:04:21.560
Facebook could not
get the approval

01:04:21.560 --> 01:04:24.500
of the Indian government to go
beyond one million accounts.

01:04:24.500 --> 01:04:30.050
They only recently in the early
spring of 2020, late winter,

01:04:30.050 --> 01:04:32.780
got approval that they
could move up to 10 million

01:04:32.780 --> 01:04:34.380
and so forth.

01:04:34.380 --> 01:04:39.170
But it's pending further
data standardization,

01:04:39.170 --> 01:04:42.680
and it's conditional on
data standardization.

01:04:42.680 --> 01:04:45.740
And then last November,
they announced Facebook Pay.

01:04:45.740 --> 01:04:48.170
Now, that puts aside
Facebook Libra.

01:04:48.170 --> 01:04:51.740
I'm just saying their
efforts to do Facebook Pay,

01:04:51.740 --> 01:04:54.080
bringing together
Facebook Messenger,

01:04:54.080 --> 01:04:59.080
Instagram, WhatsApp
is their new effort.

01:04:59.080 --> 01:05:01.520
You can decide whether you
think they'll be successful.

01:05:01.520 --> 01:05:04.300
But it's interesting that
in some circumstances,

01:05:04.300 --> 01:05:06.940
Facebook has been very
successful, but not so much

01:05:06.940 --> 01:05:08.140
in the payment space.

01:05:08.140 --> 01:05:13.180
And even Google Wallet and
Google Pay has more adoption,

01:05:13.180 --> 01:05:17.140
and Apple Pay has more adoption
than we've seen in Facebook,

01:05:17.140 --> 01:05:18.560
as I understand it.

01:05:18.560 --> 01:05:21.560
It's hard to get
all the statistics.

01:05:21.560 --> 01:05:25.540
So it gives you a little bit
of a sense of these challenges.

01:05:25.540 --> 01:05:27.490
What's the landscape?

01:05:27.490 --> 01:05:29.720
Going to do it a little
quickly, but this

01:05:29.720 --> 01:05:30.970
is to give you that landscape.

01:05:30.970 --> 01:05:34.660
First, commercial banks and
the bank-owned networks.

01:05:34.660 --> 01:05:36.970
I put here thousands of banks.

01:05:36.970 --> 01:05:38.770
They've been around since 1784.

01:05:38.770 --> 01:05:40.660
I like taking 1784
because that's

01:05:40.660 --> 01:05:44.890
the Bank of New York here in the
US, Alexander Hamilton's bank.

01:05:44.890 --> 01:05:47.290
But the clearinghouse
literally has been around

01:05:47.290 --> 01:05:48.820
since the 1850s.

01:05:48.820 --> 01:05:51.880
It was a place where people
took physical checks,

01:05:51.880 --> 01:05:53.860
negotiable orders
of withdraw, and had

01:05:53.860 --> 01:05:57.290
to take them into a
warehouse and clear them.

01:05:57.290 --> 01:05:59.860
But even UnionPay
in China, which

01:05:59.860 --> 01:06:03.010
was formed amongst
85 banks initially--

01:06:03.010 --> 01:06:05.710
and some say maybe the
People's Bank of China

01:06:05.710 --> 01:06:09.460
owns something of it, too--
but UnionPay, these bank

01:06:09.460 --> 01:06:12.120
consortium.

01:06:12.120 --> 01:06:15.990
Next in this architecture
of the payment landscape,

01:06:15.990 --> 01:06:17.460
the card companies.

01:06:17.460 --> 01:06:20.050
I would note that
Visa was a consortium.

01:06:20.050 --> 01:06:22.380
Bank of America was
a California bank.

01:06:22.380 --> 01:06:24.810
It was not a national
bank at the time.

01:06:24.810 --> 01:06:28.230
And Bank of America wanted to
offer its California credit

01:06:28.230 --> 01:06:31.710
card across the country
and formed a consortium.

01:06:31.710 --> 01:06:34.020
It later became an
independent company.

01:06:34.020 --> 01:06:35.700
It later went public.

01:06:35.700 --> 01:06:41.320
And it's got a $373 billion
market value as of last Friday.

01:06:41.320 --> 01:06:45.870
Now, we sometimes talk about the
Big Tech firms, the big four,

01:06:45.870 --> 01:06:49.260
Microsoft, and Google,
and Amazon, and Apple.

01:06:49.260 --> 01:06:51.600
They all have market
values above this.

01:06:51.600 --> 01:06:54.930
But Visa is one of the
10 highest market cap

01:06:54.930 --> 01:06:59.470
companies in the country,
maybe in the world.

01:06:59.470 --> 01:07:02.130
And then, of course, Mastercard
and so forth, Discover

01:07:02.130 --> 01:07:03.000
and the Dow.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:05.850
So that's the base
layer, but then there's

01:07:05.850 --> 01:07:08.490
something that you and I
don't think a lot about,

01:07:08.490 --> 01:07:11.040
is payments service providers.

01:07:11.040 --> 01:07:14.760
And these companies have gone
through a significant wave

01:07:14.760 --> 01:07:16.170
of consolidation.

01:07:16.170 --> 01:07:18.270
These were data
companies basically,

01:07:18.270 --> 01:07:20.700
expounded around 20 years ago.

01:07:20.700 --> 01:07:24.030
Fiserv is an agglomeration
of three or four

01:07:24.030 --> 01:07:26.100
different companies
that have come together

01:07:26.100 --> 01:07:27.330
over the last few years.

01:07:27.330 --> 01:07:31.560
But these dominant
companies here in the US

01:07:31.560 --> 01:07:34.500
are the backbones of
the payment network

01:07:34.500 --> 01:07:37.110
right in the middle of
that earlier chart that we

01:07:37.110 --> 01:07:41.760
talked about, $45 billion to
$80 billion market value each.

01:07:41.760 --> 01:07:48.170
And now we get to the
startups starting with PayPal

01:07:48.170 --> 01:07:53.740
at $124 billion of value, and
Square, and then some companies

01:07:53.740 --> 01:07:55.960
you might not be
as familiar with.

01:07:55.960 --> 01:08:00.380
But each one of these companies
founded usually in the 20-year

01:08:00.380 --> 01:08:00.880
timeframe--

01:08:00.880 --> 01:08:03.100
I'll put Western
Union to the side.

01:08:03.100 --> 01:08:08.620
Western Union was that company
that started in the 1850s.

01:08:08.620 --> 01:08:12.590
These are publicly
traded companies.

01:08:12.590 --> 01:08:14.040
You can look at
their financials.

01:08:14.040 --> 01:08:17.500
If you were actually going to
go and compete in this space,

01:08:17.500 --> 01:08:20.080
I'd largely recommend you've
got to pull these financials,

01:08:20.080 --> 01:08:23.950
read their public statements,
see how they make their money.

01:08:23.950 --> 01:08:26.319
But then there's the
private companies.

01:08:26.319 --> 01:08:28.850
And all I could do to
value these companies that

01:08:28.850 --> 01:08:32.649
go to Forbes and Crunchbase
and some other sources to say,

01:08:32.649 --> 01:08:35.439
what was their
last funding round?

01:08:35.439 --> 01:08:38.069
Stripe has not gone public yet.

01:08:38.069 --> 01:08:41.439
Paytm in India has
not gone public yet,

01:08:41.439 --> 01:08:43.210
but these are their
last funding rounds.

01:08:43.210 --> 01:08:49.880
Plaid was purchased for
$5.3 billion by Visa.

01:08:49.880 --> 01:08:53.120
But it gives you that
sense, putting aside

01:08:53.120 --> 01:08:55.790
whether these values
will persist or not.

01:08:55.790 --> 01:08:58.520
And there's hundreds,
thousands of other companies

01:08:58.520 --> 01:09:02.420
in this space competing.

01:09:02.420 --> 01:09:05.479
As I said, there's a
lot of consolidation.

01:09:05.479 --> 01:09:08.960
And one of the consolidations
is around payment service

01:09:08.960 --> 01:09:09.830
providers.

01:09:09.830 --> 01:09:13.310
Just in the last 18
months, four big mergers,

01:09:13.310 --> 01:09:16.819
one in Europe, three
in the US, basically

01:09:16.819 --> 01:09:21.170
consolidation in the
middle of this technology.

01:09:21.170 --> 01:09:24.380
First Data, which was one of
the biggest companies, that

01:09:24.380 --> 01:09:27.830
basically was on
the merchant side,

01:09:27.830 --> 01:09:29.840
helping merchants with
their point of sale,

01:09:29.840 --> 01:09:34.240
Worldpay that does this annual
report that I talked about,

01:09:34.240 --> 01:09:38.479
and Total Systems Services all
bought in the last 15 months.

01:09:38.479 --> 01:09:43.160
And then in Europe, Worldline
bought Ingenico, which

01:09:43.160 --> 01:09:46.370
was like a cross-Europe merger.

01:09:46.370 --> 01:09:47.810
But we're seeing
a lot of mergers

01:09:47.810 --> 01:09:50.359
also in the data
aggregator side.

01:09:50.359 --> 01:09:52.130
Visa bought Plaid,
as we talked about.

01:09:52.130 --> 01:09:56.300
And SoFi recently announced for
over $1 billion buying Galileo.

01:09:56.300 --> 01:09:59.350
Galileo is a smaller
competitor of Plaid

01:09:59.350 --> 01:10:02.890
that is in this API
data aggregators

01:10:02.890 --> 01:10:06.200
space, a really important
space in payments.

01:10:06.200 --> 01:10:09.890
SoFi, which we'll talk about
in our next couple of classes,

01:10:09.890 --> 01:10:15.810
started as a credit provider,
not in the payment side.

01:10:15.810 --> 01:10:19.100
But here it's interesting that
SoFi is going back and saying,

01:10:19.100 --> 01:10:20.930
we want to get to
that payment side.

01:10:20.930 --> 01:10:26.620
We want to acquire
Galileo and the API side.

01:10:26.620 --> 01:10:30.160
And so a little talk, and we've
only got a few minutes left.

01:10:30.160 --> 01:10:32.420
We already talked
about crypto projects,

01:10:32.420 --> 01:10:35.140
but the crypto land is here.

01:10:35.140 --> 01:10:39.910
And they're saying
maybe a digital token

01:10:39.910 --> 01:10:42.710
backed by US dollars
or backed by Euro

01:10:42.710 --> 01:10:47.170
or yen would be the way to
address these pain points.

01:10:47.170 --> 01:10:49.240
Some are retail projects.

01:10:49.240 --> 01:10:51.760
Mostly tether and others
on the retail side

01:10:51.760 --> 01:10:54.280
are about cryptocurrency
exchanges.

01:10:54.280 --> 01:10:56.740
But the wholesale
projects are interesting.

01:10:56.740 --> 01:10:59.080
14 large banks
have come together

01:10:59.080 --> 01:11:01.390
and formed this
thing called Fnality

01:11:01.390 --> 01:11:04.420
without an I. It's F-nality.

01:11:04.420 --> 01:11:07.300
JP Morgan has said
JP Morgan Coin.

01:11:07.300 --> 01:11:13.550
These are trying to use digital
tokens representing Fiat money

01:11:13.550 --> 01:11:15.620
to smooth out pain points.

01:11:15.620 --> 01:11:17.900
And then the messaging
companies, Telegram,

01:11:17.900 --> 01:11:22.160
the world's largest secure or
encrypted messaging company

01:11:22.160 --> 01:11:25.670
with 400 million
members or customers,

01:11:25.670 --> 01:11:28.490
they're trying to have a token
called GRAM, even though it's

01:11:28.490 --> 01:11:30.650
held up in the
securities law case

01:11:30.650 --> 01:11:32.690
that they have with the
Securities and Exchange

01:11:32.690 --> 01:11:34.910
Commission here in the US.

01:11:34.910 --> 01:11:36.420
And that sets the stage--

01:11:36.420 --> 01:11:38.200
I'm going to skip over--

01:11:38.200 --> 01:11:42.230
that Bitcoin and all of these
payment tokens are out there

01:11:42.230 --> 01:11:44.360
and talk about the goals
they're trying to do.

01:11:44.360 --> 01:11:47.810
The goals they are trying
to do are the same things--

01:11:47.810 --> 01:11:50.240
addressing pain points,
extending settlement

01:11:50.240 --> 01:11:54.890
to 24 hours a day, 7 days
a week, and lowering costs.

01:11:54.890 --> 01:11:59.000
That's why JP Morgan
has JP Morgan Coin.

01:11:59.000 --> 01:12:01.100
It might be a
little bit of hype,

01:12:01.100 --> 01:12:02.930
but there's some
reality, too, that they

01:12:02.930 --> 01:12:07.250
think that between their project
and this competitive project

01:12:07.250 --> 01:12:09.620
Fnality at the
wholesale payment space,

01:12:09.620 --> 01:12:14.270
they can lower cost in
the cross-border space.

01:12:14.270 --> 01:12:17.390
So Facebook comes along, and
Facebook says, well, maybe we

01:12:17.390 --> 01:12:18.830
can do it.

01:12:18.830 --> 01:12:22.040
Maybe we can do it with
a worldwide currency.

01:12:22.040 --> 01:12:24.000
They announced it was--

01:12:24.000 --> 01:12:25.715
it didn't lack ambition.

01:12:25.715 --> 01:12:30.860
Mark Zuckerberg and Facebook
announced a new global currency

01:12:30.860 --> 01:12:33.080
to meet the needs of
billions of people.

01:12:33.080 --> 01:12:35.270
They talked about
financial inclusion.

01:12:35.270 --> 01:12:37.910
They talked about
cross-border pain points.

01:12:37.910 --> 01:12:41.240
And they said, this is
the wave of the future.

01:12:41.240 --> 01:12:45.360
It's run into a lot of central
bank concerns around the globe.

01:12:45.360 --> 01:12:48.590
It's run into
significant public sector

01:12:48.590 --> 01:12:50.760
concerns around the globe.

01:12:50.760 --> 01:12:53.900
It's still uncertain
whether it will take off,

01:12:53.900 --> 01:12:56.930
but it's a significant
feature of this payment space

01:12:56.930 --> 01:13:00.290
that one needs to
understand, even if it's just

01:13:00.290 --> 01:13:02.060
a catalyst for change.

01:13:02.060 --> 01:13:06.500
Both China and the US reacted
quickly with the FedNow project

01:13:06.500 --> 01:13:10.490
here in the US and the
central bank digital currency

01:13:10.490 --> 01:13:12.740
project in China.

01:13:12.740 --> 01:13:15.050
So I'm going to close on
just a little chart that

01:13:15.050 --> 01:13:18.005
shows Libra versus central
bank digital currency

01:13:18.005 --> 01:13:21.230
and just say something
about China's project.

01:13:21.230 --> 01:13:25.310
China's project, not yet
lived, digital currency

01:13:25.310 --> 01:13:28.910
electronic payment
program, the issuer

01:13:28.910 --> 01:13:30.650
is the People's Bank of China.

01:13:30.650 --> 01:13:33.800
And this is a really
important question that

01:13:33.800 --> 01:13:36.410
is on a lot of people's mind.

01:13:36.410 --> 01:13:40.520
If a central bank issues a
digital representation of money

01:13:40.520 --> 01:13:46.620
directly, what's the role
of the commercial banks?

01:13:46.620 --> 01:13:48.480
Commercial banks
in most countries

01:13:48.480 --> 01:13:51.300
are the issuer of digital money.

01:13:51.300 --> 01:13:54.480
I know we think about central
banks in the 180 countries

01:13:54.480 --> 01:13:57.330
that have money, and
they're really important.

01:13:57.330 --> 01:14:00.360
But it's commercial banks
that keep those ledgers.

01:14:00.360 --> 01:14:04.080
The commercial banks with some
backing of their governments,

01:14:04.080 --> 01:14:07.740
either implicit or explicit
with deposit insurance,

01:14:07.740 --> 01:14:11.940
you and I have a liability to
our banks, to Bank America,

01:14:11.940 --> 01:14:15.650
to Barclays, to
some bank in Asia.

01:14:15.650 --> 01:14:17.550
The People's Bank
of China is saying,

01:14:17.550 --> 01:14:20.730
no, we will issue this
directly, but we'll

01:14:20.730 --> 01:14:23.880
have the commercial
banks involved.

01:14:23.880 --> 01:14:26.580
And the commercial banks,
you'll get your digital wallet

01:14:26.580 --> 01:14:27.780
from the commercial banks.

01:14:27.780 --> 01:14:31.050
There were announcements
as of early April 2020

01:14:31.050 --> 01:14:36.330
that update us, but we don't
yet have the full picture.

01:14:36.330 --> 01:14:40.020
It looks like it's basically a
centralized private network run

01:14:40.020 --> 01:14:41.670
by the PBOC.

01:14:41.670 --> 01:14:44.550
It does look like
Alipay and WeChat Pay

01:14:44.550 --> 01:14:46.840
will have to use this system.

01:14:46.840 --> 01:14:50.730
So some question is, how
different will it really be?

01:14:50.730 --> 01:14:56.070
It looks like by government Fiat
rolled out by city and region

01:14:56.070 --> 01:14:59.250
that merchants will
have to accept DCEP.

01:14:59.250 --> 01:15:01.620
So the QR system
on those buses will

01:15:01.620 --> 01:15:06.240
have to have DCEP,
Alipay, and WeChat Pay.

01:15:06.240 --> 01:15:08.700
Alipay has taken out
a bunch of patents

01:15:08.700 --> 01:15:12.210
already on how to
interface with DCEP.

01:15:12.210 --> 01:15:14.370
So it's a work in
progress, but it's

01:15:14.370 --> 01:15:15.980
an important feature of this.

01:15:15.980 --> 01:15:18.630
And if you're thinking
about payments,

01:15:18.630 --> 01:15:19.710
this is really important.

01:15:19.710 --> 01:15:22.440
And what's fascinating is
central banks around the globe

01:15:22.440 --> 01:15:25.370
are then looking to
see what China's done.

01:15:25.370 --> 01:15:30.720
Sweden was already looking at an
electronic digital central bank

01:15:30.720 --> 01:15:33.300
currency, the E-krona.

01:15:33.300 --> 01:15:35.520
And they were at the forefront.

01:15:35.520 --> 01:15:38.190
But now you can go central
bank around central bank.

01:15:38.190 --> 01:15:39.780
France has made announcements.

01:15:39.780 --> 01:15:43.020
The United Kingdom has
made announcements in 2020,

01:15:43.020 --> 01:15:48.180
all in this milieu of, how
do we address pain points?

01:15:48.180 --> 01:15:51.390
Do we as a central bank have a
responsibility to our citizens

01:15:51.390 --> 01:15:55.290
to continue to offer a digital
currency when the paper

01:15:55.290 --> 01:15:57.060
currency is going away?

01:15:57.060 --> 01:15:59.130
And important public
policy questions of,

01:15:59.130 --> 01:16:00.090
what does this do?

01:16:00.090 --> 01:16:02.950
Does it destabilize
commercial banks?

01:16:02.950 --> 01:16:07.230
So I think that's
a bit of a wrap.